Horace tells us (Sat. 1. 6⁷ 114) that he was fond of standing by the astrologers in the Circus, and listening to their predictions, without any great saith in thern: in Carm. 11. 17, 17—22 he uses the language of astrology merely as poetical ornament, and in a manner which shows his own indifference to it3 in Carm. 1. 11 he condemns it as an idle superstition.
